(18, 1, '2016-03-17 12:28:32', '2016-03-17 12:28:32', 'When Mark Zuckerberg came up with the Facebook idea his key driver was, for sure, not building a virtual empire that has changed the world we live in ever since, and definitely not generating a net worth of $33 billions a number that over 100 countries in world don’t have the luxury to earn as their GDPs. The guy just wanted to have fun, and probably express his programming prodigy.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe question is; does it really matter what was his motive? If the result was as life changing for over one billion persons around the globe, who cares what was the guy thinking of?. The answer is “yes the motive matters”, and what is more important is the motive of the adapters. So many revolutionary ideas throughout the human history have started from a pure scientific discovery driven by a mere purpose to improve human lives, but the development of those discoveries went haphazard. It’s enough to mention the “nuclear power” and you will get the idea. As communication experts we are bound to go the extra miles to explore the main drivers that generate adopters but as human beings we should make sure that the human values and well being are at the core of our approach to embrace the innovations for a greater purpose.\r\n\r\nAs Mark Twain once said “everyone is a moon, and has a dark side which he never shows to anybody” so can you imagine 7 billions dark sides interconnected with a complex physical and virtual algorithms with no control? It’s time to pause and reevaluate our personal and social identities from a morale point of views. What we are really looking for from this interconnectivity? Are we being diluted in our virtual profiles? Is even the state of being still holds the same values we had before jumping into the virtual oceans? Now, more than ever, our sensible selves should take the lead while cruising the new digital era, the temptations to diverge and live in the shade of our dark sides are becoming so widely common. Moreover, the signs we’re receiving from the future are intimidating, the reliance on machines to replace the human’s role is growing bigger and bigger. Needless to say, some of those innovations will definitely improve the quality of our lives (i.e: renewable energy, Genomics etc..) but some of them, in my opinion, will create major danger for the mankind’s fate if fallen under the wrong motives (i.e: living machines, robotic army, genetic engineering etc..)\r\n\r\nWe have to always remember that the main reason for technology adoption is driven by a need to improve the quality of life and let our “bright side” take the call, machines after all created to serve us and not the other way around. Let’s not turn our virtue of choosing into a curse, let’s not lose the one thing that differentiate us from machines “our sensibility”.\r\n\r\nPosted', 'Man vs Machine', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '5-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-03-17 12:28:32', '2016-03-17 12:28:32', '', 5, 'http://localhost:8888/inhouse/alt-wp-theme/2016/03/17/5-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(22, 1, '2016-03-17 12:31:26', '2016-03-17 12:31:26', 'I was like “dude it’s really weird, I’ve visited a movie for Maz Jobrani on Youtube and few hours later I was bombarded with his page posts on my Facebook account, how the heck did that happen?”. My techy friend “you’re being watched bro” with a smirky smile. I admit, I was digitally naïve and I deserved the smirk.\r\n\r\nBut since then, I started to look around my shoulders every time I utilize the internet, however the more paranoid I get about staying under the cyber radar the clearer I get that it’s absolutely impossible to stay disguised, and being digitally profiled is inevitable.\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n\r\nIn today’s world of “internet of things” and the ability for servers to store an enormous amount of data about almost everything, we are faced with a new era of “datafication”, an era where the world we know is about to change and for good. Our dependency on the internet to manage our lives’ requirements is growing by the day, from buying online to utilizing the search engines to clicking, sharing and liking on social media platforms etc… Today, it’s assumed that the amount of information stored online is 1,500 exabytes per year (1 exabyte is 1 billion gegabytes), it’s an amount much bigger than the whole stored information throughout the human history from Adam and Eve till the emergence of internet, and the bing bang yet to come.\r\n\r\nPutting the above in perspective with a quote once Francis Bacon mentioned in sixteenth century “Knowledge is power” we come to a conclusion that we are sadly under the mercy of damn powerful data sucker monsters that will redefine our notion of “datafication”; before the big data revolution the human kind was split between left brainers and right brainers while analyzing a piece of information based on the person genome’s structure, however, today with these data monsters’ approach, I am afraid we are going the “no brainers” route.\r\n\r\nThe way datafication works under the “big data” platforms is simply by correlating enormous amount of dumb informations to come up a smart average. It’s an approach that no doubt has added value to different aspects of mankind’s life, from buying the cheaper air ticket online to validating how “gluten free friendly” the city I am visiting as my next holiday destination, and the examples can go on and on. Having said this, the drawbacks are very threatening if we embrace the “big data” in an autopilot mode.\r\n\r\nMoving into this new world will require us to rethink about the way we should marry between the proliferated data matrix and our ability to add qualitative measurements to maintain certain humanly benchmarks. No two persons will dispute the fact that people’s virtual profiles in most of the cases vastly vary from their physical profiles due to so many sociological and psychological reasons, but it’s always debatable which side is the true one. Bridging the two ends of these profiles is something that modernized “datafication” alone cannot solve, for the mere fact that we will remain always a mysterious specie driven by complex sets of motivations that cannot be depicted from our behaviors.\r\n\r\nTherefore, in another word, we need a human to understand a human fellow and connect with him. Obviously, the context will determine whether the “big data” or the “qualitative” should rule in that connection process.\r\n\r\nSo, in order to avoid being a “01” in a matrix world or victim renegade a la “minority report”, we have to democratize the “big data” and keep questioning it and make sure it’s there to serve us and not the other way around.\r\n\r\nAfter all, I am not a big fan of Maz Jobrani, I just opened a link a friend of mine has sent me.', 'Data Minding', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-03-17 12:31:26', '2016-03-17 12:31:26', '', 1, 'http://localhost:8888/inhouse/alt-wp-theme/2016/03/17/1-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
